Spectacular "wingsuit" jump over Bogota
Sportsman Jhonathan Florez jumped from a helicopter over Bogota, the Colombian capital, on Thursday.
Equipped with a wingsuit (a combination with wings), it passed at 160 km/h above the famous Monserrate sanctuary, located at more than 3,000 meters above sea level, where many Badauds had gathered to observe its feat.
A black box in your car?
While planners of the U.S. road network struggle to find the money needed to repair derelict highway infrastructure, many are seeing a solution in the form of a small black box that fixes itself above your car’s dashboard.
The devices, which record all the miles traveled by a motorist and pass the information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government offices planning to overhaul the outdated system of financing major U.S. roads.
The generally uninterested sector of the planning of the major axes has suddenly provoked a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to lobby for the government to use small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly the road you travel on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress are unable to agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking for how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental trip.
This is truly essential for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, director general of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will start recording the miles traveled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more than a mile with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a payment system per mile.
“This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage usage charge.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces city liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state’s ambitious laws on global warming.
But Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Supporters of the Reason Foundation’s free market also appreciate the idea of having drivers pay per mile.
“It’s not just a tax lurking in a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Secretary of Transportation who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the mile payment route.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that reportedly involved about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who must travel many miles every day to get to work or town.
However, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's most important experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state mileage fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is trying a test on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the U.S. east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) is studying how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with a device, drivers were worried that the government could follow their every move.
“Worries about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads the Nevada Department of Transportation’s strategic performance management.
It's not something that people want.
From the beginning of the trial, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged localization devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily commutes and arrivals.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to call on a small California startup called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists who pay taxes to states.
She was looking to break into the emerging auto insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices it tests have liked the planners of the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
“People will be more inclined to do that if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less costly means and far less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering drivers different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all state residents.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a charging device that would also be equipped to pay for parking fees, provide “pay-to-drive” insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automakers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them,” said a document on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate on mileage payment is not just a huge diversion.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the Highway Trust Fund’s bankruptcy by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional single or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid vehicle drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so everyone pays their fair share.
“There’s no need to resort to radical surgery when you just need aspirin,” Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs, said.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four unreleased tracks
The English musician has not finished surprising this year.
From The Next Day, published in January, he has concocted a luxury reissue scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone pantose.
On the day of his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he announced that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dated 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that he could still be relied on to sparkle the pop scene.
A feast for his fans
Unsurprisingly, David Bowie had more than one lap in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke is set to re-release this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he made a real feast for his fans.
This reissue, titled The Next Day Extra, will be presented in the form of three discs: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four clips already unveiled.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks of the Deluxe edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie also made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own prints, a booklet with lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a taste of his new Atomica title, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with guitars far ahead and a skilfully mastered rock electricity.
Unreleased songs are already being listened to
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-faced: a disturbing intro before a light ride that slows down gradually to make way for a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a small reference to Elton John’s Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, on the other hand, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again makes reference to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
The guitar riffs, enchanting, make you want to leave the Earth.
In any case, Bowie has fun playing the chameleon with these titles: turn-by-turn informant, man on board a rocket, Martian potential...
He hides and reveals both, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, notably with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in his hand in the photography of Louis Vuitton’s L’Invitation au Voyage campaign, of which he embodies the new face.
It will appear in one of their commercials, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before their return to civilian life.
Attacked by the Liberals and the New Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr. Nicholson ensured that prior to their release, members of the military were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers receive appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them are released before they are ready, he said.
Detractors accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured military personnel - who do not meet the army's "universal service" rule requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
They cited two cases reported by The Canadian Press, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist in London, Ontario, suffering from post-traumatic stress disorder, was released from the army despite his request to stay another year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case came after that of Corporal Glen Kirkland, who told a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed to the exit before being ready because he did not meet the universality rule of service.
Mr. Hawkins stressed that a soldier could be prepared to leave, with plans and consultation sessions, but that this was totally different from wanting to leave the ranks.
“I told them I wasn’t ready,” he said in an interview with The Canadian Press on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was a way for me to stay, and they said no.
Since the start of major fighting in Afghanistan, the military has struggled to determine what latitude it can give to wounded soldiers who want to stay in the ranks but who are not fit for combat.
Under current rules, severely injured soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for deployments abroad, they may be forced to leave the military.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicated that of the 1,218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the length of service required to obtain retirement benefits.
Former combatant liberal spokesman Jim Karygiannis called for Corporal Hawkins' reinstatement on Wednesday, while New Democrat Jack Harris called for an immediate end to "this shameful practice."
