However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In his letter, Mr. Snowden wrote that he thought the support of the international community could persuade the U.S. government to drop the criminal charges against him.
As part of the complaint filed by the U.S. Department of Justice, he is accused of espionage and theft of state property.
German Interior Minister Hans-Peter Friedrich told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is ready to speak to German officials, we will make that possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany have been severely strained following complaints that the NSA had tapped the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
