Frontier Airlines plans to pay for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for passengers carrying carry-on baggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for a carry-on and $2 for a coffee or soda, though in its announcement Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them on the plane’s descent.
The new carry-on baggage charges relate to bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if fees were paid in advance and $100 if travelers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 was planned to encourage travelers to pay the fees in advance.
“We don’t want to make this price pay,” she explained.
The airlines started to pay for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these charges put as much stuff as they could into hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no more room in those compartments.
These fees are a way to ensure that passengers carry less stuff on board.
O'Malley said that these new fees will not really be used to raise money.
It’s about making Frontier’s most loyal customers understand that it’s becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger queued at a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's website and check-in procedures are changing to ensure passengers are aware of these charges before arriving at the door.
Frontier’s carry-on baggage charges will not be applied until the summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often sneeze about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are high and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street consider the addition of baggage fees as a sign that airlines are paying high enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
Yet many of them have not touched the cost of luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. had applied the first hand luggage fees three years ago, and the low-cost Allegiant followed a little later.
The only other company imposing such a fee is the Hungarian airline Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely follows the surcharge.
He estimated, in a December 2011 report, that Spirit’s carry-on baggage cost $50 million per year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently traveled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the boarding gate at the time passengers would discover the company’s unusual carry-on baggage charges.
“I had never seen such a smooth boarding procedure in my entire professional career,” he said.
I expected to see teeth grinding and a fight breaking out at the door.
The plane was full, he added, “passengers are on board at lightning speed.”
Frontier also does as Spirit and charges a $2 fee for a coffee, tea, soda, or fruit juice.
Frontier indicated that passengers who take a soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who take coffee can be served for free.
It will always distribute water for free.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for the drinks in 2008 but came back seven months later after passengers complained and when no other major airline had followed.
Frontier's decision to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not purchase their ticket directly from the airline is its last effort to encourage customers to go to its site.
Airlines pay online travel sellers like Orbitz $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This has prompted all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them instead of contacting an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began offering only half a mile of loyalty to customers who bought their ticket through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, it reduced mileage premiums by 25% on a trip.
For example, a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased from an online travel agency would earn 250 miles.
It also allows passengers to choose their seat in advance only if they purchase their ticket directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but her business is shrinking and she is losing money.
Revenue fell 9% and its flight capacity declined almost 13% in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic tried to fix Frontier's finances by selling the airline.
The NSA calls into question an “internal error” and not hackers for the failure of its website
The National Security Agency working in the shadows said Friday that it was a bug that had caused its public site to crash for a few hours, and not hackers as some had claimed online.
“NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update,” the spy agency said in an emailed statement.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Allegations that the failure was due to a distributed denial-of-service (DSO) attack are false.
Earlier tonight, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still can’t access the site.
Earlier, an NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency’s sensitive internal network was “not at all” compromised.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesman said.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed responsibility for the breakdown of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses.
Cyber-tactics are not very sophisticated and the attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the targeted system.
The formerly top-secret NSA, a time known as the “No Such Agency,” has found itself under the spotlight and heavily criticized in recent months following a wave of revelations about its vast communications surveillance programs at home and abroad – which are part of the NSA’s secret files stolen from the agency and leaked to the NSA.
This growing controversy around the agency has sparked much speculation that the incident tonight was the result of a targeted cyber operation.
The Delta City Centre is now closed
The Delta Centre-Ville hotel closed its doors Thursday in Montreal, after 36 years of existence.
The investment fund that owned the building sold it to promoters who will turn it into student residences.
Three hundred and fifty people worked at the hotel.
Of these, 200 have still not found a new job.
Delta promises not to drop its employees.
Employers came to meet employees directly on site, and employees were individually met to assess their needs.
“This support will continue for the next six months,” said Felix Bisson, Regional Director of Labor Relations at Delta Hotels.
The closure of the Delta is taking place in a very competitive hotel market.
The investment fund that owned that building had choices to make.
Either he reinvested in the building to continue operating it, so there were investments of tens of millions while the competition is very fierce, there are many new hotels that have appeared in Montreal.
“Or he was selling it to someone else and that’s what happened,” says Paul Arsenault, chair of Transat Tourism at the UQAM School of Management Sciences.
Other Montreal hotels will also be converted in the coming months, such as the Crown Plaza, which will become a residence for the elderly.
In the meantime, four hotel projects totaling nearly 600 rooms will be launched within two years.
