Bombardier’s profit falls as deliveries and aircraft orders fall
Bombardier Inc., a Canadian aeronautical and rail manufacturer, reported a 15% decline in its net profit on Thursday, under pressure from lower orders and deliveries of aircraft during the third quarter and contractual issues in its Trains division.
Montreal-based Bombardier has also not provided flight test data for its all-new CSeries aircraft or information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial commissioning schedule before September next year.
After the inaugural flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, the latter flew only three times, and the question then arose whether the test phase was on track.
The results were not up to expectations and the share price fell by 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday, moving from “overperformance” to “sector performance” due to the low potential for the stock market to rise in the next quarter or two.
“Although the decline in aircraft deliveries was largely anticipated, we are really disappointed by the profit margin in the Transport division,” Doerksen said in a customer note.
We believe Bombardier will record new orders for its CSeries aircraft as the flight testing program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will be able to catapult it into the lower segment of a market today dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delay.
But the number of firm orders for CSeries aircraft is so far modest at 177. It seems that potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to validate the company's claims regarding the energy efficiency and savings potential of the new airliner.
At present, the company has registered a total of 403 orders and purchase commitments from 15 customers and operators.
Pierre Beaudoin, President and Chief Executive Officer, is convinced that Bombardier will achieve its goal of 300 firm orders before the commercial commissioning of the first aircraft.
Leaders also reassured analysts and the media on Thursday by telling them that the program was moving ahead according to schedule.
“The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected,” Beaudoin said at a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were scheduled during the plane’s downtime.
Each manufacturer plans in a different way.
We decided to make a first flight and schedule an update period, and that's what we did.
This will be repeated throughout the flight program.
