YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders, globally representative of all business sizes, sectors and regions of Great Britain.
The findings of the investigation will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of companies are now looking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and developing while EU states are stagnating.
They want the government to give priority to new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than get entangled in the long and arduous process of reforming European institutional arcana.
When asked for their opinion on specific policy issues – ranging from the regulation of monopolies to product laws – the majority of business leaders believe that control of these key skills should be returned to Westminster.
The single market has caused widespread discontent, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels Regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trading zone – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, and more importantly, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority wanted Britain to pursue initiatives in favour of a treaty change and the development of a relationship with the EU based on trade rather than politics.
This conclusion, which is found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the corporate world is insisting on a “significant change” that restores power to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving a change in the treaty and better representing Britain’s interests would see a 16% drop in votes in favour of keeping the country in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate for a moment: this survey shows that British companies support this plan aimed at renegotiating the terms of Britain's accession to the EU.
It also shows that companies hope that the renegotiation will constitute a significant change in the current balance of power in favour of a return to the UK.
It is possible, and increasingly necessary, to better represent the interests of British businesses, as the euro area commits itself to a closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be employment and growth in Britain and, as the findings of our survey show, for businesses this means refocusing on trade and a fundamental change in the regulatory approach to Brussels.
