How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Finished the passwords to type to access his smartphone or pay for his purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers are predicting a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Morpho’s deputy general manager, even believes that “the century will be biometric.”
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a world as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 and in France alone, the Commission nationale de l’informatique et des libertés authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism in some, and pessimism in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will enable new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most commonly used biometric data are fingerprints, the outline of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
“For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable,” said Philippe Robin, Technical Director of Identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - it is not possible to capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes needs to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
By increasing the accuracy of sensors and the computing capacity of computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we’re conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospects at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers law enforcement a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing a person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
The identification has so far concerned the issue of identity documents: it is necessary to compare the biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) with the information that the state has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person is not trying to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or a store.
“We retrieve images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities who move freely on the Internet,” says Dany Nassif, NEC France’s commercial development manager for biometric identification solutions.
Another use: take a picture of a quidam that queues in a store, track its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend pointing for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and in Angoul<0xC3><0xAA>me by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and brands of the large distribution: when paying in store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is expected to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tips for Reassuring Users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to the biometrics, a customer stays in checkout thirty seconds less, it is appreciable,” explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailor-made options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it,” said Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, due to the lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts, for example, continue to be concerned.
“The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras, and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr, or Picasa, scare me the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
