Scientists have just highlighted how a dog’s tail movements are related to its mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals’ heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won’t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films featuring other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor – and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going more left or right.”
When the animals saw a dog without expression moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog moving its tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deflecting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog shaking the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you repeatedly meet other dogs and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tails to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience.”
The researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Sciences, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, “Dogs go more easily to a robot dog when its tail moves to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
