A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off Australia’s northern coast.
Thibaut Bouveroux, in charge of scientific mission at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Are you surprised by the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin?
This is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
If in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our knowledge in the science of species classification.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or membership of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being challenged because of advances in genetics.
In the same way, two very close morphological species have been distinguished by genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the humpback dolphins of the Pacific and humpback whales of the Atlantic.
Recent analyses have distinguished four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of individuals existing on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from neighbouring stocks.
With respect to the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This mixing of genes limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
It is preferable to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Mariana Trench, only 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent on the search for life on other planets than on marine research, and it is high time that this changed.
