Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents in Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, so white, in the immense space that is the Maisonneuve Theatre, advances, of profile, fine as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, a Henri Michaux ink is projected.
The body, a simple line, takes its form.
And this form will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only the hands and face uncovered, wait on each side of the playing area, rush when the next graphic appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in solo relays, in a unison group (a mass that makes solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
We think of "Glory of the morning", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on posters, posed online at the front stage.
This is the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is strong, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur will take refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, micro in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monocord and monotonous in the shout, and will continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - image creation has always been a strength at Chouinard - like those hairs that get dizzy or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
It seems that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, imposed herself, with her tics.
The result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt forms, open a wider and gibbous imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the ending, in the negative, with its dancers chopped by a stroboscopic light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches the magic.
The public liked it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopédies, after the intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in gray, the dancers and a piano are covered in fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their misdirections in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in love duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons, also familiar to Chouinard, appear, with red noses, in very polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnivores, runaways, or gamblers.
Gestures, laughter and small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, grace and ridicule of coit bodies, of merging beings.
But the piece takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the cabotage dancers, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness are transpiring, and it is Chouinard’s art there to contaminate the public.
