A case of rabies detected in a cat in the Val-d'Oise
Authorities announced Thursday that a case of rabies had been detected in a kitten in the Val-d'Oise, apparently of foreign origin, while France has been free of indigenous cases since 2001.
The kitten was found on October 25 in Argenteuil and died on October 28.
The diagnosis of rabies was confirmed by the Pasteur Institute.
"An epidemiological investigation has been initiated to identify and take care of people who may have come into contact with this kitten between October 8 and October 28 inclusive," the Ministry of Health and Agriculture said.
"Five people who have been in contact with the kitten have already been identified" and received preventive treatment.
"In humans, the preventive treatment of human rabies, administered after contact with the carrier animal, but before the onset of symptoms, is very effective," the statement said.
Departments are now calling for persons who would have been bitten, scratched, scratched, or licked on a mucous membrane or skin damaged by this kitten or whose animal would have been in contact with this kitten between 8 and 28 October to contact on 08.11.00.06.95 between 10 a.m. and 6 p.m. from 1 November.
“As France has been free of rabies since 2001, this kitten or mother has been imported from another country, not free of rabies,” the statement said.
The Ministry of Agriculture states that the last "indigenous" case of rabies recorded dates back to December 1998 on a fox and that "France was officially declared free of this disease in November 2001 by the International Office of Epizooties (OIE)".
A case of rabies on a dog illegally imported from The Gambia had been registered in 2008.
"Rabies is a deadly disease if not treated in time," the ministry said, and it can be transmitted for nearly 15 days before the first symptoms of the disease appear.
