John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that U.S. spying “had gone too far inappropriately.”
John Kerry has indicated a softening of the United States’ defensive attitude towards its surveillance programs by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, espionage “has gone too far inappropriately.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, like Barack Obama, ruled on “automatic pilot” when a series of incendiary revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about NSA spying activities emerged.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr. Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have become aware of certain things in automatic pilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War and up to the difficult years of the Cold War, then of course September 11."
He later became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. spying had gone beyond limits, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make clear to people that he is now undertaking a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels misled.
I assure you that innocent people will not be victims of abuse as part of this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We have indeed prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered because we have been able to get to know the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. spying case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counterterrorism efforts with the United States, the president of the Senate subcommittee on European affairs said Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made regarding a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations due to the frustration of surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It’s really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stay by our side in the mutual commitment to fight terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chair of the US Senate’s subcommittee on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
And I'm going to go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA's programs.
The press reports that the NSA has intercepted millions of communications in Europe, which has damaged relations with some US allies, however the director of the agency said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the US.
Other revelations cited documents released by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other heads of state.
The Director of Intelligence, James Clapper, justified the spying of the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a trip to Congress, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of other participating legislators are expected to be revealed in the coming days.
He indicated that the route remained to be defined.
Murphy stated that the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “affectionate firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state need to be honest with their citizens about the type of spying programs they have been implementing themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world doing espionage,” Murphy said.
In the meantime, Kerry has planned to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to deal with the resentment generated by U.S. strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as by U.S. surveillance activities.
